summary: Friendly reminder that before season 7 Michele Clapton also spoiled Jonerys things by talking about her outfit choices for both...
body:
Friendly reminder that before season 7 Michele Clapton also spoiled Jonerys things by talking about her outfit choices for both Dany and Jon in their scenes together, before any official promo or trailers had even suggested that they would meet. 

I don’t think a costume designer is coached on what to say and do the way that a cast member is. I think this could be legit.

title: Jon's Exile
excerpt: At the beginning of A Game of Thrones Eddard disinherits Jon Snow and exiles him for the rest of his life to the most distant and frigid outpost of Westeros. Having raised his son to be a member of the aristocracy and trained him to be a northern “knight,” it is hard to understand why a father wh...
description:
The Wall is the cesspit of Westeros and the Watch is the collection of its vilest inhabitants.

Sending your 14-year old son to spend the rest of his life there is about as vile a thing you can do to him. Especially given that he doesn’t know what he is letting himself in for.

This notion that it is honorable to go and serve in this stupid, outdated and meaningless Brotherhood is utterly laughable.

Put a thousand-strong garrison of trained Northmen on the Wall, drawn from the entire North as part of the fealty owed to the Starks. Rotate them annually with a new group of 1000 men, and they would be ten times as effective as the collection of man-whores, rapists, thieves, beggars and child molestors currently stationed there.

And then you would not need them to swear those stupid vows either.

100 men from each of the primary Stark bannermen would already give you around 1500 men for the Wall. And when the Wildlings raise a king once a century, and try and march on the Wall in force, just call the North’s banners, and crush them with the 20,000 cream of the North’s fighting strength.

In fact, Stannis did it with 1500 men. The Starks could do it as easily.

So coming back on topic. Having Jon throw his life away rotting away in fellowship with the dregs of the world up on the Wall, is utterly cruel. But of course, it was needed for the story to progress, so therefore people just dismiss the immensity of the event with the wave of a hand.- Free Northman Reborn

summary: You’re all invited to the Jonsa Book Club! Whether you’ve never read the books before, or you’ve lost count of how many times...
caption:
You’re all invited to the Jonsa Book Club! Whether you’ve never read the books before, or you’ve lost count of how many times you’ve read them, we want you! To get through the hiatus until season 8 begins, we will be going through the ASOIAF books together with a particular focus on Jon and Sansa’s chapters. We can learn from each other, explore foreshadowing and make parallels. Things are always much more fun when you do it together!

The book club takes place on discord, which is an app you can download to your phone/mobile device or computer. It also functions as a in-browser app (discordapp.com) so downloading is optional. It’s a public group, click this link to join: https://discord.gg/J5Unpcu

We begin with A Game of Thrones, and each book is divided into 8 week cycles. 

Week One July 29-August 4: Prologue & Chapters 1-9 (focus on Chapter 5, Jon I, though both Jon and Sansa make appearances in all of these Winterfell chapters)

Week Two August 5-11: Chapters 10-15 (focus on chapters 10 & 15, Jon II and Sansa I)

Week Three August 12-18: Chapters 16-25 (focus on chapter 19, Jon III, though Jon will be making appearances in Tyrion’s chapters at this point, and Sansa in Ned and Arya’s)

Week Four August 19-25:  Chapters 25-33 (focus on chapters 26 & 29, Jon IV and Sansa II)

Week Five August 26-September 1: Chapters 34-44 (focus on chapters 41 & 44, Jon V and Sansa III)

Week Six September 2-8: Chapters 45-52 (focus on chapters 48, 51 and 52, Jon VI, Sansa IV and Jon VII)

Week Seven September 9-15: Chapters 53-63 (focus on chapters 57 and 60, Sansa V and Jon VIII)

Week Eight September 16-22: Chapters 64-72 (focus on chapters 67 and 70, Sansa VI and Jon IX)

summary: Why Ned let Jon join the KW knowing of his heritage?
title: Why Ned let Jon join the KW knowing of his heritage?
excerpt: So I know many think Jon is not a Targ bastard. But if you think that, it makes Ned a huge asshole for basically allowing Jon to give up his right on the IT and to be tied forever to the NW. If he is a bastard then it makes sense because Jon has no claim anyway
description:
So yes, Ned could have done anything he wanted with Jon, without telling him about him the truth, and Jon could have lived out his life quietly with honor and had children, but first Ned kept him to close to protect him and then he condemned to NW, the one place where people must join with open eyes. Ned did what was convenient for him, not what was best for Jon

More than half of the Watch consists of criminals, who’ve raped, murdered and done worse things. Yea,that sounds like a perfectly safe place to send his 14 year old nephew. Mance was also a looming threat for the Watch and Ned even mentions how he might need to rally all the North to stop him, because he doesn’t believe the Night’s Watch is strong enough to stop him alone. So even without the Others, Ned was sending his nephew to live an extremely dangerous life.
